1. CRITICAL: Segmentation produces 1963 barfly segments and only 5 interpolations.
   The exercise expects 60-120 barfly and 10-30 interpolation segments. The script
   splits on single newlines (treating each line as a paragraph), which is too
   fine-grained. Cyclops interpolations may span many lines but each individual
   line can fall below the length/formality thresholds. Fix by either:
   (a) merging consecutive lines into true paragraphs (split on blank lines or
       double newlines), or
   (b) using a sliding-window approach that considers multi-line blocks, or
   (c) adding more interpolation markers (e.g., patterns like catalog lists,
       epic epithets, mock-heroic openings).

2. Class imbalance renders accuracy meaningless. With 1963 vs 5 segments, a
   majority-class baseline scores 99.7%. The reported 0.992 accuracy is not
   evidence of classifier quality. Either fix segmentation (item 1) or report
   balanced accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 per class.

3. Barfly similarity metric lacks discriminative power. The formula
   (1 - abs(diff)) * 0.5 produces values near 1.0 for all episodes because the
   feature values are small decimals (0.001-0.03). Consider using ratio-based
   similarity, cosine similarity over the full feature vector, or simply ranking
   episodes by raw feature distance rather than a normalized score.

4. Exercise 2 asks for a "barfly probability score" for every paragraph in
   Ulysses so far, computed by the trained classifier. The script instead uses
   a hand-coded similarity formula on episode-level features. Implement the
   classifier-based scoring: for each paragraph in each prior episode, extract
   features, call classifier.prob_classify(), and report P(barfly).

5. Exercise 3 asks for comparison against real-world genre corpora (e.g., NLTK's
   reuters corpus for legal/journalistic text). The script only compares against
   Calypso as a baseline. Adding at least one external corpus comparison would
   better test the "parody exceeds its source" hypothesis.

6. Only 5 interpolation segments means Exercise 3 features like passive_rate,
   exclamation_rate, and adj_prop are unreliable (several show 0.00). Fixing
   item 1 would cascade into more meaningful amplification ratios.

7. The script does not sub-classify interpolations by genre (legal, epic,
   journalistic, biblical, etc.) as the exercise requests. This is a significant
   missing piece -- the exercise specifically asks students to further classify
   interpolation types and compare each to its source genre.

8. No DecisionTreeClassifier comparison is implemented, despite the exercise's
   Diving Deeper section and the import at the top of the docstring mentioning it.

9. The extract_features() function returns raw floats for features like ttr and
   avg_word_len. NLTK's NaiveBayesClassifier treats numeric features as discrete
   labels, not continuous values. This means each unique float becomes its own
   category, which cripples the probability estimates (most test values will be
   unseen). Consider binning continuous features into discrete ranges (e.g.,
   avg_sent_len: 'short'/'medium'/'long') for more meaningful classification.
